[1] French Polynesia
Date: Thu 16 Oct 2014
Source: Le Monde [in French, trans. CopyEd.LMI, edited]
http://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2014/10/16/chikungunya-le-stade-epidemique-atteint-en-polynesie_4506877_3244.html


Chikungunya: epidemic stage reached in French Polynesia
-------------------------------------------------------------------
French Polynesia is now at the epidemic stage, after the 1st case of chikungunya was revealed last Friday [10 Oct 2014], the local government announced on Wednesday, 15 Oct [2014]. The local Health Department identified 59 cases, and 200 were considered "suspicious". However, only 3 patients are hospitalized for the time being.

On Friday, the government announced 1st 15 cases concentrated in a town in the south of Tahiti. The health authorities hoped to nip in the bud the beginning of this epidemic by destroying its vector, the mosquito, by spraying insecticide in affected neighborhoods.

The number of cases has quadrupled
-------------------------------------------
This was not enough: not only has the number of cases quadrupled in 5 days, but other islands are now affected. Patients have reported symptoms of chikungunya in Tubuai, Raiatea and Apataki Atoll. In Tahiti, 11 communes of the south and east are now affected.

Chikungunya [virus infection] causes high fevers with aching joints. In some cases, these pains and stiffness persist for several months or even several years. The disease can be fatal in vulnerable patients, especially the elderly.

The local Health department asked the public to "take action against the number one enemy, the mosquito", by destroying mosquito breeding sites. He also indicated that he had ordered a "containment P3 laboratory" to anticipate the introduction of Ebola in French Polynesia. But given the strong international demand, this laboratory might not be delivered for "4 or 5 months".

