******
[2] Tahiti
Date: Tue 14 Oct 2014
Source: TNTV [in French, trans. CopyEd.LMI, edited]
http://www.tntv.pf/Chikungunya-l-hopital-de-Taravao-est-deborde_a2935.html


Chikungunya: The Taravao hospital is overwhelmed
-----------------------------------------------------------
The Chikungunya outbreak is spreading. Since Friday [10 Oct 2014] the Taravao [Tahiti] hospital doubled its activity. More and more patients complain of chikungunya symptoms: fever and severe joint pain. The hospital has a hard time coping, especially because there is no cure for chikungunya.

The hospital has increased from 30 patients a day to nearly 70. But not all have chikungunya. There are currently 10 confirmed cases in Taravao. But none of the patients was hospitalized. Chikungunya can occur for 3 to 4 days only. Some people may have more serious symptoms like nausea and never get better.

According to the Pasteur Institute, the chikungunya virus is endemic mainly in South Asia and Africa. In 2005, a large outbreak of chikungunya hit the Indian Ocean islands including the Isle de la Reunion, with hundreds of thousands of reported cases.

In 2007, the disease emerged in Europe, where the _Aedes albopictus_ vector mosquito is established. The 1st indigenous cases in the south of France were recorded in 2010. At the end of 2013 and 2014, chikungunya spread to the Caribbean and reached the American continent.

